  <span id="freeText8907392569055232554" style="display:none">RAGE<br /><br />While he was a senior in high school Stephen King began a novel called, “Getting It On.” In the intro to a collection called, “The Bachman Books”, (four novels king originally published under the pen name Richard Bachman) King says he found the manuscript moldering away in a box in the basement of his home in 1970. He thought it was worth finishing and he did... almost got it published two years before Carrie was finally accepted. Then later, still thinking it was worth publishing he decided to bring it out under the name, “Rage.” Still, later he pulled the book from circulation because of the subject matter. At a time when American kids were walking into schools and killing bullies, tough teachers, and anyone else who got in their way, he thought the subject matter was just a little too incendiary, especially because, in this book, the kids being held hostage in the classroom start to side more and more with the killer. <br />Charlie Decker hates his father. The guy has bullied and beaten up Charlie all his life. In one nightmarish memory from an early hunting trip, 11-year-old Charlie lies in the tent and listens as his dad tells his friends how he would disfigure his wife’s face if he ever caught her cheating on him. It’s a pivotal moment for Charlie and one he sites again and again. <br />Charlie’s father-hatred eventually transfers to other cruel authority figures and erupts when a teacher begins to ridicule him in front of the class for not understanding a Physics problem. Charlie has brought a rusty pipe wrench to school with him and he attacks the teacher with it. In spite of everything, the school reduces the charges, investigates the problem, and decides to send Charlie to a school for troubled kids. While the investigation continues Charlie is allowed to attend school. But on the day the story takes place, the principal calls Charlie into his office, tells him to get his things together and go home. Turns out that was a major mistake. Charlie goes back to the classroom and, when the teacher asks him if he has a pass to get back into class, Charlie pulls out a gun and shoots her right in the head. <br />Then he takes over the class, holds off the school administration, the police and the firefighters as he and his hostages wait. He’s made it clear that he intends to shoot one of his classmates if anyone from the outside tries to take him. Still, little by little, all but one kid (Big man on campus, Ted Jones) begins to sympathize and even side with Charlie. <br />The boys and girls start to discuss their lives, their fears and even their sexual adventures, (the first time they “did it,” and with whom.) And, in then end, the class gangs up on Jones who has stood against Charlie through the whole hostage drama. They nearly kill him. <br />As in The Long Walk, this early work by King shows his brilliant insights into the personalities and relationships between young people under stress... how they band together, forgive some, and continue to hate others. There are raging hormones on all sides, and sexual excitement, confusion, disappointment and wonder seems to play a part in what’s going on. <br />This book has been related to several actual school shootings in American (several school shooters have had copies of the book.) And even though Charlie does not seem to be motivated by peer bullying, his problems with authority may have given focus to some of these events. Charlie’s fellow students offer what must seem to be a surprising response to having a genuine terrorist in their midst, they start to see him as a kind of hero and turn on the one kid in the class who is openly against him. Unfortunately, it’s a realistic portrayal of the complex and difficult position kids are often in, not knowing who is really on their side or where their hopes should lie. They’re bombarded with mixed messages from a thousand different directions. More than anything it’s a testimony to King’s brilliance that he’s captured this world so honestly. <br /></span>
