  <span id="freeText13172947893459054707" style="display:none">The Stephen King Goodreads Discussion Group is doing a re-read of his works from the beginning to the end. It’s been a long time since I have really immersed myself in Uncle Stevie’s world, but a rate of a book a month, I am all in. My goal is to read and review each one with as much honesty and reflection that I can give. <br /><br />Background – “Rage” was the first novel by Stephen King published under the pseudonym of Richard Bachman, originally published back in 1977. Because the novel describes a school shooting, which is a rather sensitive topic, King allowed the novel to go out of print. The only primary way to read it is to find it in a used bookstore in either the individual form or in the omnibus version of “The Bachman Books”. Length-wise it is a short novel. My softcover omnibus paperback lists it as 131 pages. <br /><br />Plotline – This is a controversial story (in many regards) about a troubled high school senior, Charlie Everett Decker. Charlie is back in school following his suspension for striking his chemistry teacher with wrench, hospitalizing and nearly killing him. The story opens with Charlie having an explosive confrontation with the principal, retrieving a hidden pistol, setting his locker on fire, and returning to his algebra class where he shoots his teacher and takes the class hostage. <br />That’s just the beginning. The rest of the story plays out over the next several hours as the class takes part in their own twisted version of “The Breakfast Club”. As the police gather outside and try to take control of the situation, the students hold their own psychotherapy session as Charlie’s troubled past is revealed, including a warped relationship with his abusive father. <br /><br />Thoughts and Reflections – This book is full of raw emotional anger. It is told trough Charlie’s voice in a no hold’s barred style. As I read it again for the first time in many years, two primary thoughts struck me. First, it really feels like an eighteen- year old is telling the story. It’s disjointed, bounces around between the current action and impacting memories. Charlie is juvenile in his language and thoughts because that’s what he is. He comes across like a disturbed young man’s mindset would sound like. Second, one of King’s greatest strengths was letting his “inside” voice come out in his writing. He would say the things we think but never say or admit out loud. But I think King had an even angrier and sarcastic deeper voice that I will call his “inside inner” voice. I really feel like that writing books under the pseudonym of Richard Bachman was about King letting that “inside inner” voice (the one where we would never admit things to ourselves) come out full force like a fully pressured firehose. Writing as Bachman, King is dark, satirical, and downright angry about things. I would even venture to say these books might have been a cathartic and cleansing experience for him. <br /><br />Other Notes – This book was originally titled “Getting It On” but was change before being published to “Rage”. <br /><br />Overall – This is definitely a book that makes some strong statements. Still, you can tell King wrote it in his early years when he was still developing as a writer. There are some plot and character challenges, but it still holds up enough to create a strong emotional response from the reader no matter what your personal beliefs and philosophies are. It’s not a read for enjoyment sake, but rather one that makes you think about how family, friends, and social activities can influence your behavior and how you see yourself for good or for bad. <br /></span>
